545. Epidemiology. 1990 Mar;1(2):134-40. doi: 10.1097/00001648-199003000-00009.

Predicted reduction in lung cancer risk following cessation of smoking and radon 
exposure.

Ennever FK(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Environmental Health Sciences, Case Western Reserve University 
School of Medicine, Cleveland, OH 44106.

Recently there has been considerable public and regulatory concern that radon, 
produced by the decay of naturally occurring uranium, can accumulate in homes, 
offices, and schools at levels that may substantially increase the risk of lung 
cancer. The major cause of lung cancer is smoking, and radon appears to interact 
multiplicatively with smoking in causing lung cancer. Thus, the most effective 
way to reduce the increased risk of lung cancer resulting from radon exposure is 
to cease smoking. In this paper, a model for the risks associated with radon 
exposure that was developed by a committee of the National Academy of Sciences 
is used to calculate the benefits, in terms of reduction in lifetime risk of 
lung cancer, of ceasing to smoke, ceasing radon exposure, or ceasing both. 
Ceasing to smoke is considerably more beneficial than ceasing radon exposure, 
and thus policymakers addressing the health effects of radon should place 
priority on encouraging individuals to stop smoking.

DOI: 10.1097/00001648-199003000-00009
PMID: 2073500 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


