566. Sov Zdravookhr. 1990;(12):3-7.

[Demographic processes in the countries of Eastern Europe 1945-1990].

[Article in Russian]

Shchepin OP, Vladimirova LI.

An analysis is made of changes in the demographic processes in the countries of 
Eastern Europe over the period from 1945 to 1990 within both the general 
regularities and national peculiarities according to the parameters of statics 
and dynamics of population movement. The positive tendencies in the demographic 
processes are pointed out, first of all in infant mortality rates and mean 
expectation of life at birth in Eastern European countries by decades reflecting 
the peculiarities of changes as compared with developed countries.

PIP: Demographic trends in 7 Eastern European countries are reviewed with 
special emphasis on changing political climate and health priorities. From 1950 
to 1988, the total population in Eastern Europe grew by 32,920 thousand people, 
while the population in East Germany actually decreased by 1,743 thousand 
people. During 1938-1987, the birth rate showed marked decrease: 1.86-fold in 
Romania, 1.76-fold in Bulgaria, 1.74-fold in Yugoslavia, 1.68-fold in Hungary, 
1.57-fold in Poland, 1.32-fold in East Germany, and 1.18-fold in Czechoslovakia. 
The decrease in the birth rate was associated with an overall increase in the 
divorce rate and decrease in the marriage rate. The highest increase in the 
divorce rate was recorded in Poland (2.95-fold), while the lowest (no number 
given)--in Rumania. By 1960, an overall mortality rate (per thousand people) 
showed a decrease, as compared with the pre-war period (from 14.1 to 7.5 in 
Poland and from 13.7 to 8.1 in Bulgaria). Later, the mortality rate started to 
show a gradual increase., In 1987, the highest mortality rate was recorded in 
Hungary (13.4), followed by East Germany (12.9), Bulgaria (12.0), Poland, 
Romania and Czechoslovakia (10.1-11.5). The lowest mortality rate was recorded 
in Yugoslavia (9.2). In all Eastern European countries, the infant mortality 
rate showed a steady decrease (from 9.62-fold in Bulgaria to 5.24-fold in 
Yugoslavia). Average life expectancy increased by 27.8 years in Romania, by 21.2 
years in Poland, by 19.4 years in Bulgaria, by 18.9 years in Hungary, by 12.4 
years in Yugoslavia, and by 3.4 years in East Germany. The increase in life 
expectancy resulted in significant aging of the population.

